05758nam a22006975i 9783110354782DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20142014gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)951149574  a97831103547827 a10.1524/97831103547822doi  a(DE-B1597)413827  a(OCoLC)886684631  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aInternet AccessbAEGMCT 7aART0150002bisacsh04a686.20945/3110903200aGalileo's O. nVolume III, pA Galileo Forgery ; Unmasking the New York Sidereus Nuncius /ced. by Horst Bredekamp, Irene Brückle, Paul Needham. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter (A), c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (102 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGalileo's O ;vVolume III00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tI Fruitful Doubts, May-June 2012 -- tII The Evidence of the Forged Printing -- tIII The Evidence of the Forged Paper -- tIV The Evidence of the Forged SNML Sammelband Book Structure -- tV The Evidence of the Forged Padua Compasso Book Structure -- tVI Results of non-destructive Instrumental Analysis. XRF-, FTIR-Spectroscopy and Microscopy -- tVII Towards a Psychology of the Forger -- tVIII Final Thoughts -- tPhoto Credits0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aGalileo's O, Band III, ist in der Buchgeschichte ohne Vorbild. Ein Kreis von Spezialisten der Kunst-, Buch-, Wissenschafts-, Material- und Restaurierungsgeschichte korrigiert in diesem Werk die eigenen Ergebnisse der ersten beiden Bände. In deren Zentrum stand das New Yorker Exemplar von Galileis "Sternenboten" (Sidereus Nuncius) von 1610. Die Analyse war als Beispiel einer umfassenden Kooperation gedacht, und zahlreiche Ergebnisse sind nach wie vor gültig, doch das zentrale Objekt hat sich als Produkt einer internationalen Gruppe von Fälschern erwiesen. Indem Band III die Chronologie und die Methoden dieser Entdeckung beschreibt, könnte er eine Art Wasserscheide im andauernden Wettstreit zwischen den immer feineren Methoden von Fälschern und den neuen Methoden darstellen, ihnen auf die Spur zu kommen. Das Buch ist schließlich auch ein Psychogramm von Spezialisten, die gleichsam gegen sich selbst forschen, um vergleichbare Irrtümer in Zukunft zu vermeiden.  aGalileo's O, Volume III, is perhaps without peer in the history of the book. In this work, historians in various fields revise the results they presented in the first two volumes, which focused on the New York copy of Sidereus Nuncius, written in 1610. The analysis of this book was conceived as a uniquely multidisciplinary and cooperative undertaking, and many of its findings remain valid. Yet the subject of analysis proved to be the work of an international group of forgers. Volume III describes the chronology and methods by which the discovery of forgery was made - a veritable watershed moment in the continuing struggle between the ever-more refined methods of forgers and new methods used to apprehend them. Ultimately, the work also provides insight into the psychology of specialists who "research themselves" in order to prevent similar errors in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aPrintingzItalyzVenicexHistoryy17th century. 0aRare booksxForgeries. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh1 aBredekamp, Horst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBredekamp, Horst, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrückle, Irene, econtributo